{"questionId":"33577421","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>A car is travelling along a straight residential street with speed bumps placed at regular intervals on the road to encourage safer driving. The car travels at a minimum velocity when passing over speed bumps and reaches a maximum velocity in between speed bumps.</p>\n<p>Its velocity, in <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo> </mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math>, can be modelled by the function <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>v</mi><mfenced><mi>t</mi></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo> </mo><mi>cos</mi><mo> </mo><mfenced><mrow><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi><mn>14</mn></mfrac><mfenced><mrow><mi>t</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></mfenced></mrow></mfenced><mo>+</mo><mn>9</mn></math>, where <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>t</mi></math> is measured in seconds.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Find the time at which the car first reaches its maximum velocity.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>19</mn></math> (seconds)<em><strong> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </strong><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p style=\"text-align:right;\"><em><strong>[1 mark]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"33577421","referenceCode":"24N.2.SL.TZ1.9c","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"Find the time at which the car first reaches its maximum velocity.","paper":"2","level":"SL","questionNumber":"c","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 1]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 3— Geometry and trigonometry","Topic 5 —Calculus","Topic 5 —Calculus","SL 5.9—Kinematics problems","Topic 3— Geometry and trigonometry","SL 3.7—Circular functions: graphs, composites, transformations"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}